<div class="page">
  <div class="card">

    <div class="eyebrow">Start here</div>
    <div class="amber-rule"></div>
    <h1 class="h-title">How to read this operating model.</h1>
    <p class="h-sub">An <strong>interactive Future State Blueprint</strong>. Built so every key player can see themselves in the future world and work with us on how to move there &mdash; across every discipline of BAU.</p>

    <!-- ===== SCOPE EXPLANATION: head-on, before the framing ===== -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">About the scope</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">What we were asked for, and what we built.</h2>
      <div class="honest">
        <p>The original brief was a <strong>commercial Target Operating Model</strong>. As the work moved, it became clear the commercial question (what vehicle delivers this, and how) couldn&apos;t be answered properly without showing the operating reality the vehicle has to support. You can&apos;t size a commercial model in the abstract. So we took the initiative and went wider.</p>
        <p>The commercial model is still here. <strong>It is the spine of the artefact and it informs every layer.</strong> But it now sits inside a broader frame, alongside the architecture, the lifecycle, the cast, the open questions and the human stories that make the commercial choices testable. That broader frame is a <strong>Future State Blueprint</strong>: the bridge between where the service is today and the future operating model the programme is building towards.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== SECTION 1: This isn't a frozen operating model ===== -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">First, the framing</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">This isn&apos;t a frozen operating model. It&apos;s an interactive Future State Blueprint.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">A target operating model, in the traditional sense, is a snapshot &mdash; what &lsquo;good&rsquo; looks like at a point in time. Useful, but static. This is more than that. It carries the snapshot inside it, alongside the present-day reality and the moves between them. And it stays live as the work moves.</p>

      <!-- Central insight from the work -->
      <div class="ecosystem-callout">
        <div class="ecosystem-callout-eyebrow">The central insight this is built around</div>
        <div class="ecosystem-callout-line">The service only works if the ecosystem works.</div>
        <div class="ecosystem-callout-body">Not technology. Not procurement. Not policy. Not the platform. <strong>The ecosystem.</strong> That is why the architecture has to hold patients, clinicians, commissioners and suppliers in the same frame, and why <strong>adoption is the first-order design requirement, not a downstream consideration.</strong> Every layer of this blueprint is built around the question: how do we build a service all of these players choose to use?</div>
      </div>

      <div class="cfc-block">
        <div class="cfc-tile">
          <div class="cfc-tile-num">01 &middot; The traditional view</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-h">A target operating model is a frozen snapshot.</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-body">It describes how the service ought to run, at one moment in time. Useful for sign-off. Useful for a board. But it doesn&apos;t hold the path from where you are now to where you need to be. And once it&apos;s signed, it ages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cfc-tile cfc-is">
          <div class="cfc-tile-num">02 &middot; What this is</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-h">A Future State Blueprint.</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-body">It shows where the service is today, where it needs to get to, and the moves between. The static TOM is one of the things it produces &mdash; not the thing itself. The same is true for the playbooks across disciplines (commercial, IG, and beyond), the position papers and the Hearts and Minds decks. The model stays live; the artefacts get reissued as the work moves.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cfc-tile cfc-why">
          <div class="cfc-tile-num">03 &middot; Why this matters</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-h">The 10 Year Plan set a destination. It didn&apos;t set out the HOW.</div>
          <div class="cfc-tile-body">This is the HOW. The architecture, the cast, the lifecycle, the open questions, the human stories. Built so every key player can see themselves in the future and contribute to the path between now and then.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== SECTION 2: Three layers ===== -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Three layers in one artefact</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">Input. Bridge. Output.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">The artefact bundles three things that traditional operating model documents keep apart. <strong>An input</strong> &mdash; where the service is today. <strong>A bridge</strong> &mdash; the interactive model you&apos;re navigating, holding what has to change and who has to do it. <strong>Outputs</strong> &mdash; the static TOM, the playbooks, the decks, the position papers. Each output is reissued as the bridge updates. <strong>This document is the bridge itself. A TOM sits at the far end of it.</strong></p>

      <div class="layers-wrap">
        <div class="layers-grid">
          <div class="layer-card layer-input">
            <div class="layer-eyebrow">Input</div>
            <div class="layer-h">Where we are today</div>
            <div class="layer-strap">Current state</div>
            <div class="layer-body">The reality the programme is working from. The live HIV service, the existing pathways, the constraints. Surfaced through the lifecycle, operational and open-questions pages.</div>
            <ul class="layer-list">
              <li>Status (what is decided, in flight, open)</li>
              <li>Operational (how things actually run)</li>
              <li>Lifecycle (the work in motion)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="layer-arrow">&rarr;</div>

          <div class="layer-card layer-bridge">
            <div class="layer-eyebrow">Bridge</div>
            <div class="layer-h">The interactive model</div>
            <div class="layer-strap">What you&apos;re navigating</div>
            <div class="layer-body">The architecture, the cast, the lifecycle, the governance, the open questions. Anchored by Why. Wrapped with Hearts and Minds, Status and Teamwork. This is the working model. It updates as the programme thinks.</div>
            <ul class="layer-list">
              <li>Why &middot; the rationale and north stars</li>
              <li>What &middot; the four-layer anatomy</li>
              <li>How / When / Who</li>
              <li>Hearts and Minds &middot; the human layer</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="layer-arrow">&rarr;</div>

          <div class="layer-card layer-output">
            <div class="layer-eyebrow">Outputs</div>
            <div class="layer-h">What the model produces</div>
            <div class="layer-strap">Tangible artefacts</div>
            <div class="layer-body">The static TOM is one of these. So are the playbooks across disciplines (commercial, IG, and beyond), the position papers, the Hearts and Minds decks, the prioritised delivery items. Each is a snapshot of the bridge at a moment. Each is reissued when the bridge updates.</div>
            <ul class="layer-list">
              <li>The static TOM (point-in-time)</li>
              <li>Playbooks (commercial, IG, &amp; beyond)</li>
              <li>Position papers</li>
              <li>Hearts and Minds decks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Ownership / co-creation strip -->
        <div class="own-strip">
          <div>
            <div class="own-block-h">Who owns it</div>
            <div class="own-block-body">The <strong>sponsor</strong> owns the Future State Blueprint. The programme delivery team produces and maintains the artefacts that feed it.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="own-block-h">How it stays live</div>
            <div class="own-block-body">The model is a <strong>co-creation tool</strong>. Stakeholders read it, navigate it, and feed back. The bridge updates as the work moves. Outputs are reissued.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="own-block-h">What it draws on</div>
            <div class="own-block-body">Other programme documents &mdash; primaries, strategies, prioritisation, evidence, governance papers. The model is a synthesis, not a parallel source of truth.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== SECTION: THREE STEPS · the service itself ===== -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">The service itself, in three steps</div>
      <h2 class="section-h">Referral. Fulfilment. Result.</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">Before you unpack the five questions, the service itself sits in three steps. <strong>Every page of this blueprint expands one or more of them.</strong> The petal that follows just gives you five lenses through which to read them.</p>

      <div class="three-steps-wrap">
        <div class="three-steps-grid">
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-eyebrow">01 &middot; Referral</div>
            <div class="step-h">Demand finds the platform.</div>
            <div class="step-body">An order can come from anywhere a clinician, citizen or screening service can legitimately raise one. The platform is <strong>client-neutral</strong> &mdash; it receives demand, it does not dictate where demand comes from.</div>
            <ul class="step-list">
              <li>Citizen, via the NHS App</li>
              <li>GP / primary care</li>
              <li>Secondary care consultant</li>
              <li>Screening / cohorting service</li>
              <li>Community pharmacy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="step-arrow">&rarr;</div>
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-eyebrow">02 &middot; Fulfilment</div>
            <div class="step-h">The kit goes out, the sample comes back.</div>
            <div class="step-body">Ordering, dispatch, sample collection, lab processing. The platform brokers the operational flow between commissioner, supplier and patient. <strong>The integration was done before anyone walked in.</strong></div>
            <ul class="step-list">
              <li>Ordering &amp; tracking</li>
              <li>Kit delivery to home</li>
              <li>Sample collection &amp; return</li>
              <li>Lab processing</li>
              <li>Supplier MI feed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="step-arrow">&rarr;</div>
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-eyebrow">03 &middot; Result</div>
            <div class="step-h">The result reaches the right place.</div>
            <div class="step-body">Back to the patient. Back to the GP record. Back to the clinician who needs to act. <strong>Reactive support paths sit underneath</strong> for results that need them.</div>
            <ul class="step-list">
              <li>Result to NHS App</li>
              <li>Result to clinical record</li>
              <li>Result to commissioner MI</li>
              <li>Onward pathway triage</li>
              <li>Reactive support for unsafe results</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="steps-anchor">Three steps describe what the service <strong>does</strong>. <strong>The five questions below describe how the model is organised to support them.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>

